California Houses price predection¶

Framing the Problem¶

The goal of this report is to analyze the relationship between various socioeconomic factors and median house values in a given dataset. We aim to understand how specific independent variables, such as median income, population, and number of households, influence the dependent variable, which is the median house value.

Conclusion:¶

in conclusion the median income vs house value seems to work the best because it has lower errors (MSE and MAE), suggesting it predicts house values more accurately.even the line looks near to all point(plot No 1.1).

However, the models that consider population and households in relation to house value don't perform as well. They have higher errors, indicating that they might not be as good at predicting house values.Additionally, if we look at Plot No. 2.1, we can see that the points are quite scattered and not closely aligned with the line. In an attempt to improve the accuracy of the line, I processed the data and removed some noise, resulting in Plot No. 2.2. However, even after this adjustment, the line still doesn't seem to provide a satisfactory fit to the data.

Appendix removing noise from median_house_value vs poluation plot:
